				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Probably tradition, as <em>Radar Scope</em> and <em>Donkey Kong</em> tiles are planar.<br /><br />The design of the NES PPU is a mash-up of the Texas Instruments TMS9918 and the <em>Radar Scope</em> arcade game's video circuit. Nintendo chose to model the PPU on the TMS9918 because of the high graphical quality of the ColecoVision port of <em>Donkey Kong</em>, an iconic early platformer whose arcade version ran on the <em>Radar Scope</em> board.<br /><br />The <em>Radar Scope</em> hardware uses 2bpp planar tiles and one attribute per column of tiles. But in practice, this becomes an attribute per row because the monitor is portrait. The TMS9918 uses 1bpp planar tiles and has a more detailed attribute layout. The NES PPU is a compromise between those two, with an attribute per 16x16 pixels.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
