				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I would turn this question around. Why would you consider packed pixels for anything less than 8bpp graphics? I don't really see much advantage at all, even if you ignore whatever the hardware has to do.<br /><br />Maybe for VRAM updates, it's better if you can do what you need to do in a single write. e.g. Attributes being in a packed format let you change one entry with a single byte sent. That in itself seems an advantage for performance, I suppose, but in all other respects I think it's really annoying to work with compared to a planar approach. Like, changing a single pixel is slower, sure, but when you start doing blocks of things that advantage just disappears, and you're left with a bunch of extra bit manipulation and masking that is a lot uglier than using planar formats where you can just rotate in one pixel at a time.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
