				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">rainwarrior wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I would turn this question around. Why would you consider packed pixels for anything less than 8bpp graphics? I don't really see any advantage at all, even if you ignore whatever the hardware has to do.</div><br /><br />From the standpoint of an artist, packed pixels make more &quot;sense&quot; for 2pp and 4pp because the layout is closer to what one sees in the end result. True, pixels may be &quot;flipped&quot; based on what ends up in the high or low nibble of a byte, but it's pretty easy to envision the layout in one's head.<br /><br />From the standpoint of programmer, packed pixels tend to be easier to work with in software. If you want to do something with a single pixel in a set of bit planes, you're going to have to pull up multiple bytes at a time and then mess around with multiple bitwise operators on each byte and shifting to figure out a value. Packed pixels, on the other hand, you can just pull up the byte with the pixel, do a bitwise and to get which one you want, then bit shift as needed. (They also play nicer when it's time to send everything off to a modern GPU, but that's a moot point for the time period in discussion.) It's also generally easier to implement simple RLE compression than most of the compression algorithms useful for bitplanes, other than the ever-useful method of dropping unneeded bit planes and making do with fewer colors.<br /><br />Granted, either way, on modern systems where RAM is a dime an acre I assume it's irrelevant for the most part since you're more likely to just cache each pixel as a 32-bit integer or RGBA/ARGB anyway. This is what the emulator source code I've looked at seems to do as well.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

