			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">OverworldTheme wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">From the standpoint of programmer, packed pixels tend to be easier to work with in software. ... with a single pixel</div><br />I think it's a minor performance advantage for a single pixel, but if you're doing single pixels performance is probably not your critical problem. For operations involving many pixels I think it's <em>far</em> worse.<br /><br />I'll explain it this way: if you're doing an operation on 2 (or more) bitplanes, you write one simple piece of code to write 1-bpp material, and then you just run it twice. If you're doing an operation on packed pixels, you have to write a more complicated piece of code that does both at the same time. For performance reasons you often end up writing an unrolled piece of code that has 4 phases to deal with the 4 packed pixels.<br /><br />At least, that's my experience with it. 1-bpp code is simple to write, and extending it to any number of planes is trivial. (This also applies to implementing it in hardware, I think.) Packed pixels breed complexity.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">OverworldTheme wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">From the standpoint of an artist, packed pixels make more &quot;sense&quot; for 2pp and 4pp because the layout is closer to what one sees in the end result.</div><br />I don't think &quot;sense&quot; is worth arguing here. This makes no more &quot;sense&quot; than choosing big endian over little endian. It's down to your personal preferences. I think any artist used to working with process inks would intuitively understand bitplanes pretty easily, for example.<br /><br />Also, the artist isn't the person who deals with the bit packing. This is a problem that is generally hidden from them, unless they're also the programmer (in which case it isn't an issue either).</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

