				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Sun Jan 22, 2012 12:03 pm<br /><b>Posts:</b> 4233<br /><b>Location:</b> Canada
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Wikipedia wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">When the later VGA was introduced, memory speeds had increased to the point where planar video modes were no longer a necessity, and aside from backwards-compatibility, using planar mode or not was left as a choice for the programmer.</div><br />I don't think this is quite accurate. VGA's only packed mode was <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mode_13h" class="postlink">13h</a>, and it was special. All the other standard modes were planar, and of course the hardware itself was planar technology.<br /><br />13h was super convenient for the programmer. Hands down, no question about that. 8-bpp works great for that.<br /><br />The underlying hardware implementation of 13h, however, was planar. Everything was planar under the hood. 13h was made possible by <em>wasting</em> 3/4 of the available video RAM. This was a good trade for an art program, or something that's not high performance, but for games it took a long while for CPUs to grow in power enough to make up for this loss of GPU efficiency.<br /><br />That's why <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mode_X" class="postlink">Dr. Dobb's Mode X exposé</a> was such a revelation when it happened. Unlocking the underlying planar implementation was a <em>huge</em> win for games where the CPU still wasn't powerful enough to do full software rendering. From a performance standpoint, mode 13h is utterly <em>crippled</em> in comparison.<br /><br />As the 90s went on, though, eventually it didn't matter, and you could just draw everything with the CPU anyway. At that point the inefficiency of 13h was irrelevant, and it was tons easier to work with.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

