				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">rainwarrior wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I think it's a minor performance advantage for a single pixel, but if you're doing single pixels performance is probably not your critical problem. For operations involving many pixels I think it's <em>far</em> worse.</div><br />Granted; computer processors are better at handling groups of things than they are at handling individual things.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">rainwarrior wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I don't think &quot;sense&quot; is worth arguing here. This makes no more &quot;sense&quot; than choosing big endian over little endian. It's down to your personal preferences.</div><br />Which is why I say &quot;sense&quot; in quotes. I do believe it's the more intuitive option, but I'm not arguing that it's the best.<br /><br />However, it can also flip around the original question: If planar graphics seem to have caught on first, why did later 2/4bpp hardware such as the Atari 7800, Genesis / Mega Drive, and GBA move to packed pixel formats?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">rainwarrior wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I don't think this is quite accurate. VGA's only packed mode was 13h, and it was special. All the other standard modes were planar, and of course the hardware itself was planar technology.</div><br />Yeah, as I noted in my earlier post I was hesitant to take Wikipedia at face value here as they only had one source for that entire paragraph, and said source didn't seem to really address anything that was specifically brought up concerning planar graphic formats.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

