				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Sun Jan 22, 2012 12:03 pm<br /><b>Posts:</b> 4233<br /><b>Location:</b> Canada
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The idea that it might facilitate a single pixel change might be the explanation why attributes on the NES are packed. Changing a single attribute tile does seem like something the designers would have expected. Writing single pixels to CHR-RAM, however, I think is pretty dubious.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">OverworldTheme wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">If planar graphics seem to have caught on first, why did later 2/4bpp hardware such as the Atari 7800, Genesis / Mega Drive, and GBA move to packed pixel formats?</div><br />Well, I already went over it with VGA, but the 8-bpp packed format was an obvious advantage once the CPU power got to a certain point. I don't think we need to think very hard to realize why GBA would have used packed formats, at least where they fit a byte/word conveniently. It's a different era with different needs.<br /><br />I'm kind of surprised by the Genesis, actually, but mostly because the Atari ST and Amiga were both planar, so I almost would have expected that to influence its design. Not that thier repsective GPUs have anything to do with each other, just that the Genesis did draw a lot of attention from developers who worked with the Amiga first.<br /><br />I haven't worked with 7800 or Genesis, so I don't really have any basis to speculate. How many bpp are we talking about with 7800 and Genesis?<br /><br />I think the strongest benefit of planar modes is just that you can support multiple modes easily (as was the case with EGA, VGA, Amiga, etc.). In hardware that only has one video mode (e.g. CGA only had the one 2-bpp mode), especially with 2-bpp it might be a wash to be multiplexing 2 x 1-bpp vs just building a 2-bpp unpacker; it might even have been an arbitrary decision in cases like the NES, maybe just somebody's preference, or due to some vaguely convenient part of the hardware's internal design. Like, obviously there's a way to make both ways work, the reason for picking one doesn't have to be iron-clad.<br /><br />Like, as a programmer, I do think I much prefer planar formats for 4-bpp / 2-bpp, but that really just comes from the work I've done with them in the past. Normally I wouldn't get to choose, I would just write whatever I need to that works for whatever platform I'm on. Programmer preference doesn't necessarily have to be a concern for the hardware design; they gotta put up with it what they get anyway.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">OverworldTheme wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I was hesitant to take Wikipedia at face value here as they only had one source for that entire paragraph, and said source didn't seem to really address anything that was specifically brought up concerning planar graphic formats.</div><br />Yeah, I actually went and revised it. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_wink.gif" alt=";)" title="Wink" /></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

