				<span class="postdetails">
					<br /><b>Joined:</b> Mon Mar 14, 2016 7:55 am<br /><b>Posts:</b> 8<br /><b>Location:</b> United States
				</span>

			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">rainwarrior wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I'm kind of surprised by the Genesis, actually, but mostly because the Atari ST and Amiga were both planar, so I almost would have expected that to influence its design. Not that thier repsective GPUs have anything to do with each other, just that the Genesis did draw a lot of attention from developers who worked with the Amiga first.<br /><br />I haven't worked with 7800 or Genesis, so I don't really have any basis to speculate. How many bpp are we talking about with 7800 and Genesis?</div><br />The Genesis's sole mode is 4bpp, if I understand correctly. It's also only got four palettes total, which I always thought was a strange choice. Even the Turbografx / PC Engine had a whopping 32 palettes (16 background, 16 sprite). I do believe the Genesis pixel format is nibble-swapped from the GBA's 4bpp modes; I assume that's because the Genesis used a big endian CPU.<br /><br />The Atari 7800 had <a href="http://atarihq.com/danb/files/7800vid.txt" class="postlink">multiple video modes with varying color depths</a>. You could choose between 1bpp, 2bpp, or 4bpp. 2bpp and 4bpp were both packed. It's worth noting that the 7800's idea of 4bpp was this monstrosity:<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">160B (160x4) Mode<br /><br />This mode has 4 bits per pixel and a maximum width of 160 pixels. The color<br />of each pixel (left to right) is determined as follows:<br /><br />pixel 0 - bits 3,2,7,6<br />pixel 1 - bits 1,0,5,4</div><br />Of course, everything about the 7800 seems strange. I've only skimmed over its specs, but it looks very much like a <em>direct</em> evolution of the 2600, which makes sense considering the backwards compatibility. The graphics are purely raster-based. You set them up scanline by scanline in a swapping buffer.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

