				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">OverworldTheme wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">By splitting the data up into multiple planes, each plane could be stored on a separate memory chip. These chips could then be read in parallel at a slower rate, allowing graphical display on modest hardware.</div><br />That's what I always thought it was, even if all the graphical data was read from one chip. It's kind of odd, because I'm under the impression that this only gave you a speed advantage on old, slow hardware, but the way I even knew about this was because of the Irem M92. Plus, if you have hardware that can select multiple color depths, isn't it easier if the graphics are planar, or semi-planar like the SNES? (It's packed only for 2bpp graphics) I think I heard it takes less circuitry because all it is is loading more data and not changing how you're loading it, so it takes less die space.<br /><br />Although none of this directly applies to the NES, like somebody said, it's like tradition, and the only way you'd know what Nintendo was thinking is if you'd ask them. I just feel like in the situation of the NES, it really didn't matter what graphics format they chose and they flipped a coin or something.<br /><br />Just thinking about people talking about bit manipulation, I kind of doubt Nintendo was concerned about this, seeing that the overwhelming majority of NES games use CHRROM. (If they wanted the NES to use ram for graphics, they could have just made the system use VRAM.)</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

